<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910725-0128</DOCNO><DOCID>910725-0128.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Deutsche Bank Tightens   Controls Over Stock Trades   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   G.DBK</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)GERMANY (GE)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   FRANKFURT, Germany -- Deutsche Bank AG has tightenedinternal controls on its stock exchange dealers' tradingactivities, Chairman Hilmar Kopper said on German television.   In advance of more stringent regulation expected fromstock exchange and government authorities, Mr. Kopper saidthat Deutsche Bank, Germany's largest bank, wants to &quot;take aclose look&quot; at its trading activities world-wide as a resultof recent embarrassing allegations of improper transactions.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Kopper said the bank's increased controls mightinclude restricting its dealers' own-account tradingactivities.   Deutsche Bank recently suspended and then fired its chiefoptions dealer, Manfred Mertens.   Although the bank denies the action had anything to dowith insider trading, the firing closely followed publicationof an anonymous letter in a German financial magazinealleging that Mr. Mertens and other Deutsche Bank officialswere involved in front-running, insider trading and taxevasion.   Mr. Kopper said that besides Mr. Mertens there had been noother &quot;personnel consequences&quot; at the bank. The bank'sinternal controls weren't at fault in the Mertens case, headded. Mr. Mertens couldn't be reached to comment.   The Frankfurt public prosecutor's office is investigatingas many as 30 dealers at German and foreign banks inFrankfurt regarding possible tax evasion related to insidertrading. Insider trading isn't illegal in Germany, althoughit is frowned upon.</TEXT></DOC>